modifications to it. "Object Code" means any non-source form of a work.

  To "modify" a work means to copy from or adapt all or part of the work
in a fashion requiring copyright permission, other than the making of an
exact copy. The resulting work is called a "modified version" of the
earlier work or a work "based on" the earlier work.

  A "covered work" means either the unmodified Program or a work based
on the Program.

  To "propagate" a work means to do anything with it that, without
permission, would make you directly or secondarily liable for
infringement under applicable copyright law, except executing it on a
computer or modifying a private copy. Propagation includes copying,
distribution (with or without modification), and making available to the
public.

  To "convey" a work means any kind of propagation that enables other
parties to make or receive copies.

  "Commercial Use" means any use primarily intended for or directed
toward commercial advantage, monetary compensation, or financial gain.
This includes, but is not limited to:

    a) Selling, licensing, or sublicensing the Program or any covered
    work, or any portion thereof, for a fee;

    b) Using the Program or any covered work, or any portion thereof, to
    provide commercial services, including but not limited to
    software-as-a-service (SaaS), platform-as-a-service (PaaS), or any
    hosted or managed service offering;

    c) Incorporating the Program or any covered work, or any portion
    thereof, into a product or service that is sold, licensed, or
    otherwise commercially distributed;

    d) Using the Program or any covered work in the course of conducting
    business operations that generate revenue, except where the Program
    is used solely as an internal tool and is not itself the basis for
    the revenue-generating activity;

    e) Using the Program or any covered work for advertising, marketing,
    or promotional purposes in connection with a commercial product or
    service.

  "Noncommercial Use" means any use that does not constitute Commercial
Use as defined above. Examples of Noncommercial Use include, but are not
limited to: personal use, academic research, educational purposes,
use by charitable or nonprofit organizations in furtherance of their
nonprofit missions, and contributions to the Program itself.

  1. Source Code.

  The "Corresponding Source" for a work in object code form means all
the source code needed to generate, install, and (for an executable
work) run the object code and to modify the work, including scripts to
control those activities. However, it does not include the work's
System Libraries, or general-purpose tools or generally available free
