            How to Apply These Terms to Your New Programs

  If you develop a new program, and you want it to be freely available
for noncommercial use while preventing commercial exploitation, you may
license it under these terms.

  To do so, attach the following notices to the program. It is safest to
attach them to the start of each source file to most effectively state
the exclusion of warranty and commercial use restriction; and each file
should have at least the "copyright" line and a pointer to where the
full notice is found.

    <one line to give the program's name and a brief idea of what it does.>
    Copyright (C) <year>  <name of author>

    This program is free software for noncommercial use: you can
    redistribute it and/or modify it under the terms of the Eventful
    Noncommercial Public License as published by the copyright holders,
    either version 1 of the License, or (at your option) any later
    version.

    This program is distributed in the hope that it will be useful, but
    WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of
    MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE. See the
    Eventful Noncommercial Public License for more details.

    You should have received a copy of the Eventful Noncommercial Public
    License along with this program. If not, see the LICENCE file in the
    source repository.

    COMMERCIAL USE OF THIS SOFTWARE IS STRICTLY PROHIBITED without a
    separate written license from the copyright holders.

Also add information on how to contact you by electronic and paper mail.

  If the program does terminal interaction, make it output a short
notice like this when it starts in an interactive mode:

    <program>  Copyright (C) <year>  <name of author>
    This program comes with ABSOLUTELY NO WARRANTY; for details type `show w'.
    This is free software for noncommercial use only; type `show c' for details.
    Commercial use is prohibited without a separate license.
